{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bbc0412d5a548dba", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                                    Adaptive Momentum Enhanced Distributed\n2\t                                                   Multichannel Active Noise Control for Faster\n3\t                                                    Convergence under Communication Delays\n4\t                                                                       Junwei Ji, Woon-Seng Gan, Boxiang Wang, Ziyi Yang, Haowen Li\n5\t                                                           School of Electrical and Electronic Engineering, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore\n6\t                                                                                Email: JUNWEI002@e.ntu.edu.sg, ewsgan@ntu.edu.sg\n7\t\n8\t\n9\t                                              Abstract—Distributed multichannel active noise control (DM-\n10\t                                           CANC) reduces the computational burden of centralized ANC\n11\t                                           systems by distributing processing tasks across multiple nodes,\n12\t                                           while requiring information exchange to achieve satisfactory\n13\t                                           global noise reduction. To improve robustness under communi-\n14\t                                           cation delays, the auto-shrink step size mixed-gradients filtered\n15\t                                           reference LMS (ASSS-MGDFxLMS) algorithm has been pro-\n16\t                                           posed. However, the reduced step size inevitably slows conver-\n17\t                                           gence. In this work, an adaptive momentum term is introduced\n18\tarXiv:2607.17165v1 [eess.AS] 19 Jul 2026\n19\t\n20\t\n21\t\n22\t\n23\t                                           to accelerate convergence, where cosine similarity is used to\n24\t                                           evaluate the alignment between the instantaneous gradient and\n25\t                                           the momentum component and dynamically adjust the mo-\n26\t                                           mentum parameter. This design accelerates convergence when\n27\t                                           the directions are consistent while preserving stability under\n28\t                                           delayed communication. Simulation results demonstrate that\n29\t                                           the proposed adaptive momentum ASSS-MGDFxLMS (AMAS-\n30\t                                                                                                                 Fig. 1. A general DMCANC network, where each ANC node consists of a\n31\t                                           MGDFxLMS) algorithm achieves faster convergence than ASSS-            secondary source, an error sensor, and an ANC controller.\n32\t                                           MGDFxLMS while maintaining stable and effective noise reduc-\n33\t                                           tion performance.\n34\t                                              Index Terms—Multichannel Active Noise Control (MCANC),\n35\t                                           distributed control, adaptive momentum, mixed-gradients dis-          signals. Although effective, the computational load grows\n36\t                                           tributed FxLMS (MGDFxLMS), auto-shrink step size (ASSS),              rapidly with the number of channels, leading to high hardware\n37\t                                           communication restrictions                                            cost and limited real-time scalability [15], [16]. To reduce\n38\t                                                                                                                 complexity, various efficient algorithms have been proposed,\n39\t                                                                  I. I NTRODUCTION                               including partial-update schemes [17], mixed-error methods\n40\t                                              By employing multiple secondary sources and error sensors,         [18], and frequency-point selection techniques [19]. As an\n41\t                                           multichannel active noise control (MCANC) systems enable              alternative, decentralized strategies distribute computations\n42\t                                           global noise reduction over large spatial regions [1]. To achieve     across multiple local controllers, each updating its control filter\n43\t                                           satisfactory performance and effectively track dynamic noise          using only local error signal [20], [21]. However, decentral-\n44\t                                           characteristics and acoustic environments, adaptive algorithms        ized methods can degrade global attenuation and may even\n45\t                                           are widely employed. Among them, the filtered reference               compromise stability due to inter-channel interference [22].\n46\t                                           least mean square (FxLMS) algorithm [2] is one of the most               Distributed MCANC (DMCANC) methods provide a\n47\t                                           classical approaches and has been extensively extended to             promising alternative [23], where each node processes local\n48\t                                           multichannel configurations [3]. In recent years, a wide range        signals while exchanging essential information to achieve\n49\t                                           of FxLMS variants have been developed to address practical            global noise reduction [24]. A typical DMCANC network is\n50\t                        