                           Adaptive Momentum Enhanced Distributed\n                                                   Multichannel Active Noise Control for Faster\n                                                    Convergence under Communication Delays\n                                                                       Junwei Ji, Woon-Seng Gan, Boxiang Wang, Ziyi Yang, Haowen Li\n                                                           School of Electrical and Electronic Engineering, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore\n                                                                                Email: JUNWEI002@e.ntu.edu.sg, ewsgan@ntu.edu.sg\n\n\n                                              Abstract—Distributed multichannel active noise control (DM-\n                                           CANC) reduces the computational burden of centralized ANC\n                                           systems by distributing processing tasks across multiple nodes,\n                                           while requiring information exchange to achieve satisfactory\n                                           global noise reduction. To improve robustness under communi-\n                                           cation delays, the auto-shrink step size mixed-gradients filtered\n                                           reference LMS (ASSS-MGDFxLMS) algorithm has been pro-\n                                           posed. However, the reduced step size inevitably slows conver-\n                                           gence. In this work, an adaptive momentum term is introduced\narXiv:2607.17165v1 [eess.AS] 19 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                           to accelerate convergence, where cosine similarity is used to\n                                           evaluate the alignment between the instantaneous gradient and\n                                           the momentum component and dynamically adjust the mo-\n                                           mentum parameter. This design accelerates convergence when\n                                           the directions are consistent while preserving stability under\n                                           delayed communication. Simulation results demonstrate that\n                                           the proposed adaptive momentum ASSS-MGDFxLMS (AMAS-\n                                                                                                                 Fig. 1. A general DMCANC network, where each ANC node consists of a\n                                           MGDFxLMS) algorithm achieves faster convergence than ASSS-            secondary source, an error sensor, and an ANC controller.\n                                           MGDFxLMS while maintaining stable and effective noise reduc-\n                                           tion performance.\n                                              Index Terms—Multichannel Active Noise Control (MCANC),\n                                           distributed control, adaptive momentum, mixed-gradients dis-          signals. Although effective, the computational load grows\n                                           tributed FxLMS (MGDFxLMS), auto-shrink step size (ASSS),              rapidly with the number of channels, leading to high hardware\n                                           communication restrictions                                            cost and limited real-time scalability [15], [16]. To reduce\n                                                                                                                 complexity, various efficient algorithms have been proposed,\n                                                                  I. I NTRODUCTION                               including partial-update schemes [17], mixed-error methods\n                                              By employing multiple secondary sources and error sensors,         [18], and frequency-point selection techniques [19]. As an\n                                           multichannel active noise control (MCANC) systems enable              alternative, decentralized strategies distribute computations\n                                           global noise reduction over large spatial regions [1]. To achieve     across multiple local controllers, each updating its control filter\n                                           satisfactory performance and effectively track dynamic noise          using only local error signal [20], [21]. However, decentral-\n                                           characteristics and acoustic environments, adaptive algorithms        ized methods can degrade global attenuation and may even\n                                           are widely employed. Among them, the filtered reference               compromise stability due to inter-channel interference [22].\n                                           least mean square (FxLMS) algorithm [2] is one of the most               Distributed MCANC (DMCANC) methods provide a\n                                           classical approaches and has been extensively extended to             promising alternative [23], where each node processes local\n                                           multichannel configurations [3]. In recent years, a wide range        signals while exchanging essential information to achieve\n                                           of FxLMS variants have been developed to address practical            global noise reduction [24]. A typical DMCANC network is\n                                           challenges encountered in real-world implementations [4],             shown in 1. The diffusion FxLMS (DFxLMS) algorithm was\n                                           such as output saturation [5], spatial reduction [6], [7], and        developed by employing topology-based combination rules\n                                           virtual sensing [8], [9]. Recently, advances in artificial intelli-   [25], [26], but its spatial-smoothing nature limits performance\n                                           gence (AI) have further stimulated the development of deep-           under asymmetric acoustic paths [27]. To address this issue,\n                                           learning-based ANC algorithms [10]–[12], offering promising           the augmented DFxLMS (ADFxLMS) algorithm and a bidi-\n                                           potential for enhanced robustness and adaptability in complex         rectional communication strategy were proposed to improve\n                                           and highly dynamic acoustic environments [13].                        robustness and reduce communication overhead [28], [29].\n                                              Conventional MCANC algorithms, such as the multiple                Recent experimental studies have further validated DMCANC\n                                           error FxLMS (MEFxLMS) approach [14], typically adopt a                using in-chip communication platforms [30].\n                                           centralized architecture:in which a single processor performs            However, these approaches are generally limited to ideal\n                                           multichannel adaptive processing using all reference and error        communication networks. Under communication latency, the-\n\foretical analysis has shown that DMCANC systems may be-\ncome unstable [31]. To address this issue, the auto-shrink step\nsize mixed-gradients distributed FxLMS (ASSS-MGDFxLMS)\nalgorithm was proposed, in which the step size at each node is\nautomatically reduced according to the degree of communica-\ntion delay [31]. While this strategy enhances stability, the re-\nduced step size inevitably slows down the convergence speed.\nTo address this limitation, a momentum term is introduced\nto accelerate convergence. To avoid instability caused by a\nfixed momentum factor, cosine similarity is used to evaluate\nthe directional consistency between the mixed gradient and\nthe momentum term [32], enabling adaptive adjustment of the\nmomentum strength. Consequently, the proposed adaptive mo-            Fig. 2. Block diagram of the ASSS-MGDFxLMS algorithm for the kth node,\nmentum ASSS-MGDFxLMS (AMAS-MGDFxLMS) improves                         where γk (n) denotes the interference generated by other nodes.\nDMCANC performance under communication latency by\nrapidly achieving satisfactory noise reduction while preserving\nsystem stability, demonstrating strong practical significance.          Based on the gradient descent method, the instantaneous\n   The remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Sec-          gradient of the local cost function at node k with respect to\ntion II reviews the ASSS-MGDFxLMS algorithm. Section III              the control filter wk (n) is given by\npresents the proposed adaptive momentum strategy to improve\nthe convergence speed of ASSS-MGDFxLMS under commu-                                 ∇k (n) = −2[x(n) ∗ ŝkk (n)] · ek (n).              (3)\nnication latency. Section IV reports numerical simulations that\ndemonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed method. Finally,        where ŝkk (n) denotes the estimated self-secondary path. Sim-\nSection V concludes the paper.                                        ilarly, the local gradients of other nodes can be computed\n         II. T HE ASSS-MGDF X LMS A LGORITHM                          following (3). Instead of transmitting the control filters as the\n                                                                      conventional DMCANC algorithms, the local gradient of each\n   In practical deployments, DMCANC systems suffer from\n                                                                      node is shared. After receiving the gradients from other nodes,\ntwo critical c